#### IRL-7: Talking to a Mechanic
*Strategy:* Prepare + Decode
*See also:* Tr-2, Ch-2
*My Man Jeeves:* _The automobile repair industry operates upon a remarkably efficient information asymmetry: the mechanic possesses specialized knowledge regarding the vehicle's condition, and the vehicle's owner possesses, in the main, the awareness that a sound has begun that was not previously present. Into this gap, one observes, a considerable amount of revenue flows. Not all of it is unwarranted — the profession is skilled and the work is genuinely necessary. But the distinction between "your brake pads are worn and you will die" and "this cabin air filter could be fresher" is one the owner ought to be equipped to make. Your Agent has read every Technical Service Bulletin for your vehicle. The mechanic may not expect that._

*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I need to take my car to a mechanic and I want to be prepared.
The situation:
— Car: [year, make, model, mileage]
— The problem: [describe the symptom — noise, warning light,
   smell, performance issue, or "it's just due for maintenance"]
— What the mechanic said (if I've already been): [describe
   their diagnosis and quote]
— My budget: [amount, or "I need to prioritize"]
Please help me:
1. Based on my car and symptoms, what are the most likely causes?
2. What is the fair price range for the repair they're suggesting?
3. Which items on this list are safety-critical (do now) vs.
   recommended (do soon) vs. upsell (can wait or skip)?
4. What questions should I ask the mechanic to show I've
   done my homework — without being adversarial?
5. Is this a repair I should get a second opinion on?
:::

*What to do with the Output:* Get the diagnosis first. Most reputable mechanics will diagnose for free or for a nominal fee. Get the diagnosis in writing before you authorize the repair. Then ask your Agent to evaluate it. The conversation you want with the mechanic is: "I understand this is the issue. I've looked up the fair price. Let's talk about the work." That's a different conversation than "I don't know what's wrong with it. Fix it."

::: meme
[Home Improvement:S1E1 "Pilot"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home%5FImprovement%5F(TV%5Fseries)%5F(season%5F1)), 1991 — Tim Taylor's entire arc is a man who would rather attempt the repair himself than admit he doesn't understand the repair. The show ran eight seasons on this premise. Do not be Tim Taylor. Know enough to have the conversation. Then let the professional do the work.
:::


::: tip
_"The mechanic says I need [repair] and quoted me [amount]. My car is a [year/make/model]. Is that a fair price? Is this urgent or can it wait until next month?"_ — Ask this before you authorize anything. Two minutes of preparation can save hundreds of dollars.
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: AAA data on average repair costs by service type. NHTSA Technical Service Bulletins are public and searchable — the reader should know these exist. RepairPal and similar pricing tools can corroborate Agent output. The FTC's "Auto Repair Basics" page has consumer rights information. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The mechanic's shop is one of the most heavily gendered information asymmetries in American life. Women report being quoted higher prices and receiving more unnecessary repair recommendations than men for identical problems. The Ian Ayres study on auto repair (building on his car sales research) documented this. The anxiety of "being taken advantage of" is not paranoia — it is a statistically validated concern. Your Agent does not change the gender dynamics in the shop. It changes whether you walk in knowing what the repair should cost. -->

