#### IRL-8: Navigating a Parent-Teacher Conference
*Strategy:* Prepare + Assert
*See also:* Li-7, IRL-3: First-Time Situations
*My Man Jeeves:* _The parent-teacher conference presents itself as a collaborative exchange regarding the child's progress. In practice, one observes, it is a twenty-minute encounter in which the teacher has prepared remarks and the parent is expected to receive them. The parent who arrives with questions — specific, informed, documented — shifts the conversation from monologue to dialogue. When the matter involves an IEP or a 504 plan, the shift is not merely social but legal: the parent is a required member of the team, with rights established by federal statute, and the school is obligated to respond to their concerns in writing. Many parents are not informed of this. The school system does not appear to regard the omission as urgent. Your Agent has read IDEA. It can prepare you to exercise rights you may not know you have._

*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I have a parent-teacher conference coming up for my
[age/grade] child.
The situation:
— What's going on: [academic concerns, behavioral issues,
   social difficulties, gifted program, IEP/504 review,
   general check-in, or "the school called me"]
— My concern: [specific worry or goal for the meeting]
— Current support: [IEP, 504 plan, tutoring, none, or
   "I don't know what these are"]
— What I want: [better communication, specific accommodations,
   a plan, answers, to understand my rights]
Please help me:
1. What questions should I ask — specific to my child's situation
2. If this involves an IEP or 504: what are my legal rights
   as a parent, and what is the school required to provide?
3. What should I document during and after the meeting?
4. What phrases signal that I'm an informed advocate without
   being combative — I want collaboration, not conflict
5. What are the red flags — things the school might say that
   I should push back on?
:::

*What to do with the Output:* Bring notes. Take notes. The single most important thing you can do in a parent-teacher conference is write down what was agreed to and email a summary afterward: "Thank you for meeting today. Here's my understanding of what we discussed and the next steps." That email is a record. If the school doesn't respond to correct it, it stands.

::: science
Under IDEA (Individuals with Disabilities Education Act), parents are equal members of the IEP team. The school cannot change an IEP without parental consent. Parents have the right to request an IEE (Independent Educational Evaluation) at public expense if they disagree with the school's assessment. Most parents don't know either of these facts.[^irl8-1]
:::


::: tip
_"The school wants to remove an accommodation from my child's 504 plan. What are my rights? What should I say in the meeting? What should I put in writing?"_ — Your Agent knows the federal framework. Your school may not volunteer it.
:::


::: fairness
Parents who speak the school's language — literally and figuratively — get better outcomes for their kids. Schools with higher-income populations have more parent engagement infrastructure. Schools with lower-income populations have larger class sizes and fewer counselors. If English is not your first language, you have the legal right to an interpreter at IEP meetings. Ask your Agent to draft the request.
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: IDEA (20 U.S.C. §1400 et seq.) and Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act — verify specific parental rights provisions. Wrightslaw.com is the definitive parent resource for special education law. COPAA (Council of Parent Attorneys and Advocates) provides free resources. The reader should know these exist. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The parent-teacher conference is one of the few institutional encounters where the power asymmetry runs through your child. The stakes feel different when the person across the table controls your kid's daily experience. Parents report feeling intimidated, dismissed, or patronized — particularly parents of color and parents without college degrees. The school system's professional vocabulary (IEP, 504, RTI, MTSS, BIP) functions as a gatekeeping language. Your Agent translates it. -->

[^irl8-1]: Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA), 20 U.S.C. §1414(d)(1)(B) — parental participation in IEP development.

