#### IRL-9: Handling a Car Accident
*Strategy:* Prepare + Navigate
*See also:* Tr-1, L-4, M-8
*My Man Jeeves:* _The fifteen minutes following a motor vehicle collision are, one might venture, among the least suitable for clear decision-making in the entire human experience — and yet they are precisely the interval during which the decisions that determine the subsequent six months of insurance negotiations, potential litigation, and financial exposure are made. What one says to the other driver, to the police officer, and to one's insurance company in those first minutes becomes the record. The record is remarkably difficult to amend. Your Agent cannot be consulted at the moment of impact, but it can be consulted ten minutes later, in the passenger seat, while you are waiting for the police to arrive._

*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I was just in a car accident. [Or: I want to be prepared
in case I'm in one.]
The situation:
— What happened: [describe briefly — rear-ended, intersection
   collision, parking lot, single car, hit and run]
— Injuries: [none / minor / serious / not sure yet]
— Other driver: [cooperating / not cooperating / left the scene]
— Police: [on scene / called / not called]
— Photos: [taken / not yet]
Please help me:
1. What do I do right now, step by step — in order of priority
2. What do I say to the other driver — and what do I NOT say
3. What do I say to the police officer
4. What do I photograph and document before I leave the scene
5. What do I tell my insurance company — and what do I not
   volunteer
6. Do I need a lawyer? When does it make sense to get one?
Give me the most conservative, legally accurate answer.
:::

*What to do with the Output:* Do not say "I'm sorry" to the other driver. Do not say "it was my fault." Do not speculate about what happened. Exchange insurance information, take photos of everything (both cars, the scene, license plates, road conditions, traffic signs), and get the police report number. Then sit in your car and read what your Agent told you before you call your insurance company.

::: tip
Save this spec on your phone now, before you need it. Change the situation details when the time comes. The moment after an accident is not the moment to learn what to do after an accident.
:::


::: meme
[Seinfeld:S7E12 "The Caddy"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The%5FCaddy%5F(Seinfeld)), 1996 — Kramer and a car accident that spirals into an insurance catastrophe because nobody documented anything and everybody assumed. The episode is a comedy. Your insurance claim is not. Document everything.
:::


::: fairness
After an accident, police reports and insurance adjusters introduce human judgment — and human bias. Studies show that fault determination and claim payouts correlate with the demographics of the parties involved, not just the facts. If you feel the police report is inaccurate, you have the right to submit a supplemental statement. Your Agent can draft it. Your record does not have to be someone else's summary of what happened.
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: State-specific rules on fault determination, no-fault vs. at-fault states, statute of limitations for filing claims and lawsuits. The "do not say sorry" advice is legally sound in at-fault states but some states have "apology laws" that make expressions of sympathy inadmissible. Verify state-by-state variation. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): A car accident is a trauma response compressed into an administrative event. Your hands are shaking, your adrenaline is spiking, and the system requires you to be a calm documentarian. The gap between your physiological state and the task at hand is the widest it will be in any entry in this book. The preparation-before-you-need-it framing is not a suggestion — it is the entire point. You cannot learn this in the moment. You learn it now. -->

---

#### IRL-10: Attending a Funeral or Memorial
*Strategy:* Prepare + Navigate
*See also:* Li-2, IRL-3: First-Time Situations
*My Man Jeeves:* _There exists no social occasion at which the fear of saying the wrong thing is more acute, or at which the wrong thing is more frequently said. Funerals and memorial services operate according to customs that vary by religion, culture, region, and family — and one is expected to navigate these customs while managing one's own grief, or supporting someone else who is managing theirs. The system provides no orientation. One arrives, one is uncertain whether to speak or remain silent, whether to bring food or flowers or neither, what to wear, what to say to the family, and what, precisely, one does with one's hands. Your Agent cannot grieve with you. It can tell you what to expect so that your attention is free for the only thing that matters: being present._

*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I am attending a funeral or memorial service and I want to
be prepared.
The situation:
— My relationship to the person: [close family / friend /
   colleague / acquaintance / I'm supporting someone who's grieving]
— The tradition: [Catholic, Jewish, Muslim, Hindu, Baptist,
   secular, military, celebration of life, "I don't know"]
— What I'm worried about: [what to say, what to wear,
   whether to bring something, the logistics, my own emotions]
Please help me:
1. What should I expect — walk me through the structure of
   this type of service
2. What do I wear? What do I bring?
3. What do I say to the family — and what should I absolutely
   not say? Give me specific sentences, not platitudes
4. What are the cultural or religious customs I should know —
   things that would be obvious to someone raised in this
   tradition but not to an outsider?
5. What do I do after — follow-up, checking in, the part
   that actually matters most?
:::

*What to do with the Output:* Read it. Showing up is the thing that matters. The fear of doing it wrong keeps people from showing up at all, and absence is always worse than awkwardness. If you don't know what to say, "I'm here" is enough. If you don't know the customs, follow the people around you. Your Agent handles the logistics so you can handle the being human.

::: meme
[Seinfeld:S6E1 "The Chaperone"](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The%5FChaperone%5F(Seinfeld)), 1994 — The show's entire run is a master class in the anxiety of social conventions. Every episode is someone doing the wrong thing at the wrong time because nobody explained the rules. Funerals are the one context where the stakes of that anxiety are real. Prepare, so you can be present instead of panicking.
:::


::: tip
The most useful thing you can do after a funeral is not say "let me know if you need anything." It is to do a specific thing without being asked — bring a meal, mow the lawn, pick up the kids, send a text in three weeks when everyone else has stopped checking in. Ask your Agent: _"My [friend/colleague] lost [person]. It's been [time]. What is a specific, helpful thing I can do right now?"_
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Grief follows no schedule and no protocol. The funeral industry in America is a $20 billion business that mediates one of the most universal human experiences through commercial transactions — and the bereaved are making purchasing decisions while in acute grief. The FTC's Funeral Rule requires price disclosure but enforcement is thin. The entry deliberately focuses on the social and emotional preparation rather than the commercial side — that could be its own entry (funeral planning, advance directives, costs). The emotional reality: many people avoid funerals entirely because the anxiety of not knowing the protocol exceeds their sense of obligation. This is the IRL-3 dynamic at its most consequential. -->

---

#### IRL-11: Job Interviews In Person
*Strategy:* Prepare + Assert
*See also:* W-1, Li-1
*My Man Jeeves:* _The in-person interview is, one might observe, a performance in which both parties have agreed to pretend that the exchange of pleasantries, the firm handshake, and the question regarding one's greatest weakness constitute a reliable method of evaluating professional competence. Research suggests they do not. The interview persists, nevertheless, because the hiring manager believes in it, and the hiring manager is the audience. What this means, practically, is that preparation for an interview is not preparation to demonstrate competence — it is preparation to demonstrate the appearance of competence to a specific person, in a specific room, for approximately forty-five minutes. Your Agent has read every question they are likely to ask. It can rehearse your answers until they sound unrehearsed._

*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I have an in-person job interview coming up and I want to
be fully prepared.
The situation:
— The role: [job title, company, industry]
— What I know about the interview: [who I'm meeting,
   format — panel, one-on-one, multiple rounds, presentation]
— My background: [brief relevant experience]
— What I'm nervous about: [specific concern — tough questions,
   salary discussion, gaps in resume, industry switch,
   body language, what to wear, small talk]
Please help me:
1. Research this company — what should I know going in,
   and what should I reference in conversation?
2. Give me the 10 most likely questions for this role
   and help me draft answers that sound natural, not rehearsed
3. What do I wear, what do I bring, and what do I do
   with my hands?
4. What questions should I ask them — the ones that signal
   I'm serious and that also get me information I actually need?
5. Walk me through the logistics: arrival time, who to ask for,
   the handshake, the small talk, the close, the follow-up
6. Help me draft a follow-up email I can send within 2 hours
   of leaving
:::

*What to do with the Output:* Rehearse out loud. Answers that exist only in your head sound different from answers you've said to a room. Practice with your Agent using voice mode if available — tell it to ask you the questions one at a time and give you honest feedback on your answers. Print the company research and your question list. Arrive 10 minutes early. Bring two copies of your resume, a pen, and a notebook. The follow-up email is the most overlooked part: send it the same day, reference something specific from the conversation, and keep it to three sentences.

::: science
Meta-analyses of interview validity (Schmidt & Hunter, 1998; updated Sackett et al., 2022) consistently show that unstructured interviews are among the weakest predictors of job performance. Structured interviews — where every candidate gets the same questions — are significantly better. You cannot control which type you get. You can prepare for both. Your Agent helps you anticipate the structure and rehearse within it.[^irl11-1]
:::


::: tip
_"I just left the interview. Here's what happened: [describe]. Help me draft a follow-up email that references [specific moment from the conversation] and reinforces that I'm the right fit for [specific aspect of the role]."_ — Do this in the parking lot. Two hours is the window.
:::


::: fairness
Interview outcomes are shaped by bias — conscious and unconscious. Identical resumes with different names receive different callback rates. Candidates who "fit the culture" are often candidates who look like the existing team. Your Agent cannot change the interviewer's biases. It can ensure that the things within your control — preparation, answers, follow-up — are as strong as possible. The structural unfairness is real. So is your preparation.
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Schmidt, F.L. & Hunter, J.E. (1998). "The validity and utility of selection methods in personnel psychology." Psychological Bulletin, 124(2), 262–274. Updated by Sackett et al. (2022). Verify both citations and DOIs. Also: Bertrand & Mullainathan (2004) "Are Emily and Greg More Employable Than Lakisha and Jamal?" — the foundational callback study on name-based discrimination in hiring. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The job interview is one of the few situations where the information asymmetry runs in both directions — the company is evaluating you, but you are also evaluating them, and most candidates forget this. The power dynamic feels one-directional because you need the job and they have the job. Your Agent can help you prepare questions that are genuinely evaluative, not performative — "What happened to the last person in this role?" tells you more than "What does success look like in the first 90 days?" The anxiety of interviewing while employed is different from the anxiety of interviewing while unemployed. The book should acknowledge both without pretending they're the same. -->

[^irl11-1]: Sackett, P.R. et al. (2022). "Revisiting meta-analytic estimates of validity of personnel selection." _Journal of Applied Psychology_, 107(4), 537–560.
